# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: line-segment-intersection
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] In geometry, an **arrangement of lines** is the subdivision of the Euclidean plane formed by a finite set of lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] An arrangement consists of bounded and unbounded convex polygons, the *cells* of the arrangement, line segments and rays, the *edges* of the arrangement, and points where two or more lines cross, the *vertices* of the arrangement.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] When considered in the projective plane rather than in the Euclidean plane, every two lines cross, and an arrangement is the projective dual to a finite set of points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Arrangements of lines have also been considered in the hyperbolic plane, and generalized to *pseudolines*, curves that have similar topological properties to lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The initial study of arrangements has been attributed to an 1826 paper by Jakob Steiner.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] An arrangement is said to be *simple* when at most two lines cross at each vertex, and *simplicial* when all cells are triangles (including the unbounded cells, as subsets of the projective plane).
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] There are three known infinite families of simplicial arrangements, as well as many *sporadic simplicial arrangements* that do not fit into any known family.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Arrangements have also been considered for infinite but locally finite systems of lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Certain infinite arrangements of parallel lines can form simplicial arrangements, and one way of constructing the aperiodic Penrose tiling involves finding the dual graph of an arrangement of lines forming five parallel subsets.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The maximum numbers of cells, edges, and vertices, for arrangements with a given number of lines, are quadratic functions of the number of lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] These maxima are attained by simple arrangements.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The complexity of other features of arrangements have been studied in discrete geometry; these include zones, the cells touching a single line, and levels, the polygonal chains having a given number of lines passing below them.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Roberts's triangle theorem and the Kobon triangle problem concern the minimum and maximum number of triangular cells in a Euclidean arrangement, respectively.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Algorithms in computational geometry are known for constructing the features of an arrangement in time proportional to the number of features, and space linear in the number of lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] As well, researchers have studied efficient algorithms for constructing smaller portions of an arrangement, and for problems such as the shortest path problem on the vertices and edges of an arrangement.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] As an informal thought experiment, consider cutting an infinite sheet of paper along finitely many lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] These cuts would partition the paper into convex polygons.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Their edges would be one-dimensional line segments or rays, with vertices at the points where two cut lines cross.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] This can be formalized mathematically by classifying the points of the plane according to which side of each line they are on.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Each line produces three possibilities per point: the point can be in one of the two open half-planes on either side of the line, or it can be on the line.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Two points can be considered to be equivalent if they have the same classification with respect to all of the lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] This is an equivalence relation, whose equivalence classes are subsets of equivalent points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The *edges* or *panels* of the arrangement are one-dimensional regions belonging to a single line.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] They are the open line segments and open infinite rays into which each line is partitioned by its crossing points with the other lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] That is, if one of the lines is cut by all the other lines, these are the connected components of its uncut points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The *vertices* of the arrangement are isolated points belonging to two or more lines, where those lines cross each other.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The boundary of a cell is the system of edges that touch it, and the boundary of an edge is the set of vertices that touch it (one vertex for a ray and two for a line segment).
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The system of objects of all three types, linked by this boundary operator, form a cell complex covering the plane.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Two arrangements are said to be *isomorphic* or *combinatorially equivalent* if there is a one-to-one boundary-preserving correspondence between the objects in their associated cell complexes.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The same classification of points, and the same shapes of equivalence classes, can be used for infinite but *locally finite* arrangements, defined as arrangements in which every bounded subset of the plane is crossed by finitely many lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] In this case the unbounded cells may have infinitely many sides.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] It is convenient to study line arrangements in the projective plane as every pair of lines has a crossing point.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Line arrangements cannot be defined using the sides of lines, because a line in the projective plane does not separate the plane into two distinct sides.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] One may still define the cells of an arrangement to be the connected components of the points not belonging to any line, the edges to be the connected components of sets of points belonging to a single line, and the vertices to be points where two or more lines cross.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] An arrangement of lines in the Euclidean plane can be naturally interpreted as an arrangement of great circles on the 2-sphere $S^{2}$ .
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] To see this, embed the Euclidean plane $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ as an affine plane $A\subset \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ not passing through the origin.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Every point of A determines a line through the origin, which intersects $S^{2}$ in a pair of antipodal points; likewise, every line in A maps to a great circle on the sphere.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The equator associated with A separates the two hemispheres and plays the role of the line at infinity.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Identifying antipodal points on $S^{2}$ yields the projective plane, where lines in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ extend naturally to great circles and parallel lines meet at infinity.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] In this way, the combinatorial structure of line arrangements, including incidences, regions, and intersections, is preserved when transferred to great-circle arrangements on the sphere.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Due to projective duality, many statements about the combinatorial properties of points in the plane may be more easily understood in an equivalent dual form about arrangements of lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The earliest known proof of the Sylvester–Gallai theorem, by Eberhard Melchior in 1940, uses the Euler characteristic to show that such a vertex must always exist.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] An arrangement of lines in the projective plane is said to be *simplicial* if every cell of the arrangement is bounded by exactly three edges.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Simplicial arrangements were first studied by Melchior.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The sides and axes of symmetry of an even regular polygon, together with the line at infinity.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Additionally there are many other examples of *sporadic simplicial arrangements* that do not fit into any known infinite family.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Conjecturally, there are only finitely many of them.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] This is known to be true under a linear bound on the number of double points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The two known counterexamples to the Dirac–Motzkin conjecture (which states that any n -line arrangement has at least $n/2$ ordinary points) are both simplicial.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The dual graph of a line arrangement has one node per cell and one edge linking any pair of cells that share an edge of the arrangement.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] These graphs are partial cubes, graphs in which the nodes can be labeled by bitvectors in such a way that the graph distance equals the Hamming distance between labels.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] In the case of a line arrangement, each coordinate of the labeling assigns 0 to nodes on one side of one of the lines and 1 to nodes on the other side.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Dual graphs of simplicial arrangements have been used to construct infinite families of 3-regular partial cubes, isomorphic to the graphs of simple zonohedra.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] It is also of interest to study the extremal numbers of triangular cells in arrangements that may not necessarily be simplicial.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Any arrangement in the projective plane must have at least n triangles.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Every arrangement that has only n triangles must be simple.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] For Euclidean rather than projective arrangements, the minimum number of triangles is $n-2$ , by Roberts's triangle theorem.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The maximum possible number of triangular faces in a simple arrangement is known to be upper bounded by $n(n-1)/3$ and lower bounded by $n(n-3)/3$ ; the lower bound is achieved by certain subsets of the diagonals of a regular $2n$ -gon.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] For projective arrangements that are not required to be simple, there exist arrangements with $n(n-1)/3+4$ triangles for all $n\geq 4$ , and all arrangements with $n\geq 6$ have at most $7n(n-1)/18+1/3$ triangles.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The closely related Kobon triangle problem asks for the maximum number of non-overlapping finite triangles in an arrangement in the Euclidean plane, not counting the unbounded faces that might form triangles in the projective plane.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Again, the arrangements are not required to be simple.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] For some but not all values of n , there exist arrangements with $n(n-2)/3$ triangles.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The dual graph of a simple line arrangement may be represented geometrically as a collection of rhombi, one per vertex of the arrangement, with sides perpendicular to the lines that meet at that vertex.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] These rhombi may be joined together to form a tiling of a convex polygon in the case of an arrangement of finitely many lines, or of the entire plane in the case of a locally finite arrangement with infinitely many lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] This construction is sometimes known as a Klee diagram, after a publication of Rudolf Klee in 1938 that used this technique.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Not every rhombus tiling comes from lines in this way, however.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] G. de Bruijn investigated special cases of this construction in which the line arrangement consists of k sets of equally spaced parallel lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] For two perpendicular families of parallel lines this construction gives the square tiling of the plane, and for three families of lines at 120-degree angles from each other (themselves forming a trihexagonal tiling) this produces the rhombille tiling.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] However, for more families of lines this construction produces aperiodic tilings.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] In particular, for five families of lines at equal angles to each other (or, as de Bruijn calls this arrangement, a *pentagrid*) it produces a family of tilings that include the rhombic version of the Penrose tilings.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] There also exist three infinite simplicial arrangements formed from sets of parallel lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The tetrakis square tiling is an infinite arrangement of lines forming a periodic tiling that resembles a multigrid with four parallel families, but in which two of the families are more widely spaced than the other two, and in which the arrangement is simplicial rather than simple.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Its dual is the truncated square tiling.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] These three examples come from three affine reflection groups in the Euclidean plane, systems of symmetries based on reflection across each line in these arrangements.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Constructing an arrangement means, given as input a list of the lines in the arrangement, computing a representation of the vertices, edges, and cells of the arrangement together with the adjacencies between these objects.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] For instance, these features may be represented as a doubly connected edge list.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Arrangements can be constructed efficiently by an incremental algorithm that adds one line at a time to the arrangement of the previously added lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Each new line can be added in time proportional to the size of its zone, linear by the zone theorem.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] This results in a total construction time of $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The memory requirements of this algorithm are also $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] It is possible instead to report the features of an arrangement without storing them all at once, in time $O(n^{2})$ and space $O(n)$ , by an algorithmic technique known as topological sweeping.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Computing a line arrangement exactly requires a numerical precision several times greater than that of the input coordinates: if a line is specified by two points on it, the coordinates of the arrangement vertices may need four times as much precision as these input points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Therefore, computational geometers have also studied algorithms for constructing arrangements with limited numerical precision.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] As well, researchers have studied efficient algorithms for constructing smaller portions of an arrangement, such as zones, k -levels, or the set of cells containing a given set of points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The problem of finding the arrangement vertex with the median x -coordinate arises (in a dual form) in robust statistics as the problem of computing the Theil–Sen estimator of a set of points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] An approximation algorithm is known, and the problem may be solved efficiently for lines that fall into a small number of parallel families (as is typical for urban street grids), but the general problem remains open.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] A non-stretchable pseudoline arrangement of nine pseudolines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] An arrangement of pseudolines is a family of curves that share similar topological properties with a line arrangement.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] These can be defined in the projective plane as simple closed curves any two of which meet in a single crossing point.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] A pseudoline arrangement is said to be *stretchable* if it is combinatorially equivalent to a line arrangement.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Determining stretchability is a difficult computational task: it is complete for the existential theory of the reals to distinguish stretchable arrangements from non-stretchable ones.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Another type of non-Euclidean geometry is the hyperbolic plane, and arrangements of lines in this geometry have also been studied.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] Any finite set of lines in the Euclidean plane has a combinatorially equivalent arrangement in the hyperbolic plane (e.g. by enclosing the vertices of the arrangement by a large circle and interpreting the interior of the circle as a Klein model of the hyperbolic plane).
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] However, parallel (non-crossing) pairs of lines are less restricted in hyperbolic line arrangements than in the Euclidean plane: in particular, the relation of being parallel is an equivalence relation for Euclidean lines but not for hyperbolic lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The intersection graph of the lines in a hyperbolic arrangement can be an arbitrary circle graph.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The corresponding concept to hyperbolic line arrangements for pseudolines is a *weak pseudoline arrangement*, a family of curves having the same topological properties as lines such that any two curves in the family either meet in a single crossing point or have no intersection.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] In a survey on arrangements, Pankaj Agarwal and Micha Sharir attribute the study of arrangements to Jakob Steiner, writing that "the first paper on this topic is perhaps" an 1826 paper of Steiner.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] In this paper, Steiner proved bounds on the maximum number of features of different types that an arrangement may have.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] After Steiner, the study of arrangements turned to higher-dimensional arrangements of hyperplanes, focusing on their overall structure and on single cells in these arrangements.
[src:line-segment-intersection/arrangement-of-lines] The study of arrangements of lines, and of more complex features such as zones within these arrangements, returned to interest beginning in the 1980s as part of the foundations of computational geometry.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] In computational geometry, the **Bentley–Ottmann algorithm** is a sweep line algorithm for listing all *crossings* in a set of line segments, i.e. it finds the *intersection points* (or, simply, *intersections*) of line segments.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] It extends the Shamos–Hoey algorithm, a similar previous algorithm for testing whether or not a set of line segments has any crossings.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] For an input consisting of n line segments with k crossings (or intersections), the Bentley–Ottmann algorithm takes time ${\mathcal {O}}((n+k)\log n)$ .
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] In cases where $k={\mathcal {o}}\left({\frac {n^{2}}{\log n}}\right)$ , this is an improvement on a naïve algorithm that tests every pair of segments, which takes $\Theta (n^{2})$ .
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] The algorithm was initially developed by Jon Bentley and Thomas Ottmann (1979); it is described in more detail in the textbooks Preparata & Shamos (1985), O'Rourke (1998), and de Berg et al.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] Although asymptotically faster algorithms are now known by Chazelle & Edelsbrunner (1992) and Balaban (1995), the Bentley–Ottmann algorithm remains a practical choice due to its simplicity and low memory requirements.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] The main idea of the Bentley–Ottmann algorithm is to use a sweep line approach, in which a vertical line *L* moves from left to right (or, e.g., from top to bottom) across the plane, intersecting the input line segments in sequence as it moves.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] No three line segments intersect at a single point.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] In such a case, *L* will always intersect the input line segments in a set of points whose vertical ordering changes only at a finite set of discrete *events*.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] Specifically, a discrete event can either be associated with an endpoint (left or right) of a line-segment or intersection point of two line-segments.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] Thus, the continuous motion of *L* can be broken down into a finite sequence of steps, and simulated by an algorithm that runs in a finite amount of time.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] There are two types of events that may happen during the course of this simulation.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] When *L* sweeps across an endpoint of a line segment *s*, the intersection of *L* with *s* is added to or removed from the vertically ordered set of intersection points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] These events are easy to predict, as the endpoints are known already from the input to the algorithm.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] The remaining events occur when *L* sweeps across a crossing between (or intersection of) two line segments *s* and *t*.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] These events may also be predicted from the fact that, just prior to the event, the points of intersection of *L* with *s* and *t* are adjacent in the vertical ordering of the intersection points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] The Bentley–Ottmann algorithm itself maintains data structures representing the current vertical ordering of the intersection points of the sweep line with the input line segments, and a collection of potential future events formed by adjacent pairs of intersection points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] It processes each event in turn, updating its data structures to represent the new set of intersection points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] The algorithm does not need to maintain explicitly a representation of the sweep line *L* or its position in the plane.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] Rather, the position of *L* is represented indirectly: it is the vertical line through the point associated with the most recently processed event.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] The binary search tree may be any balanced binary search tree data structure, such as a red–black tree; all that is required is that insertions, deletions, and searches take logarithmic time.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] Similarly, the priority queue may be a binary heap or any other logarithmic-time priority queue; more sophisticated priority queues such as a Fibonacci heap are not necessary.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] Note that the space complexity of the priority queue depends on the data structure used to implement it.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] The Bentley–Ottmann algorithm performs the following steps.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] Initialize a self-balancing binary search tree *T* of the line segments that cross the sweep line *L*, ordered by the *y*-coordinates of the crossing points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] While *Q* is nonempty, find and remove the event from *Q* associated with a point *p* with minimum *x*-coordinate.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] The algorithm processes one event per segment endpoint or crossing point, in the sorted order of the x -coordinates of these points, as may be proven by induction.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] As a consequence, it correctly finds all crossings of input line segments, the problem it was designed to solve.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] The Bentley–Ottmann algorithm processes a sequence of $2n+k$ events, where n denotes the number of input line segments and k denotes the number of crossings.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] Each event is processed by a constant number of operations in the binary search tree and the event queue, and (because it contains only segment endpoints and crossings between adjacent segments) the event queue never contains more than $3n$ events.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] All operations take time ${\mathcal {O}}(\log n)$ .
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] Hence the total time for the algorithm is ${\mathcal {O}}((n+k)\log n)$ .
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] This space bound is due to Brown (1981); the original version of the algorithm was slightly different (it did not remove crossing events from Q when some other event causes the two crossing segments to become non-adjacent) causing it to use more space.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] Chen & Chan (2003) described a highly space-efficient version of the Bentley–Ottmann algorithm that encodes most of its information in the ordering of the segments in an array representing the input, requiring only ${\mathcal {O}}(\log ^{2}n)$ additional memory cells.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] However, in order to access the encoded information, the algorithm is slowed by a logarithmic factor.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] The algorithm description above assumes that line segments are not vertical, that line segment endpoints do not lie on other line segments, that crossings are formed by only two line segments, and that no two event points have the same *x*-coordinate.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] In other words, it doesn't take into account corner cases, i.e. it assumes general position of the endpoints of the input segments.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] However, these general position assumptions are not reasonable for most applications of line segment intersection.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] Bentley & Ottmann (1979) suggested perturbing the input slightly to avoid these kinds of numerical coincidences, but did not describe in detail how to perform these perturbations. de Berg et al.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] A similar approach to degeneracies was used in the LEDA implementation of the Bentley–Ottmann algorithm.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] For the correctness of the algorithm, it is necessary to determine without approximation the above-below relations between a line segment endpoint and other line segments, and to correctly prioritize different event points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] For this reason it is standard to use integer coordinates for the endpoints of the input line segments, and to represent the rational number coordinates of the intersection points of two segments exactly, using arbitrary-precision arithmetic.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] However, it may be possible to speed up the calculations and comparisons of these coordinates by using floating point calculations and testing whether the values calculated in this way are sufficiently far from zero that they may be used without any possibility of error.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] The O(*n* log *n*) part of the time bound for the Bentley–Ottmann algorithm is necessary, as there are matching lower bounds for the problem of detecting intersecting line segments in algebraic decision tree models of computation.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] However, the dependence on *k*, the number of crossings, can be improved.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] However, constructing this arrangement as a whole requires space O(*n* + *k*), greater than the O(*n*) space bound of the Bentley–Ottmann algorithm; Balaban (1995) described a different algorithm that lists all intersections in time O(*n* log *n* + *k*) and space O(*n*).
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] If the input line segments and their endpoints form the edges and vertices of a connected graph (possibly with crossings), the O(*n* log *n*) part of the time bound for the Bentley–Ottmann algorithm may also be reduced.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] As Clarkson, Cole & Tarjan (1992) show, in this case there is a randomized algorithm for solving the problem in expected time O(*n* log* *n* + *k*), where log* denotes the iterated logarithm, a function much more slowly growing than the logarithm.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] A closely related randomized algorithm of Eppstein, Goodrich & Strash (2009) solves the same problem in time O(*n* + *k* log(*i*)*n*) for any constant *i*, where log(*i*) denotes the function obtained by iterating the logarithm function *i* times.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] The first of these algorithms takes linear time whenever *k* is larger than *n* by a log(*i*)*n* factor, for any constant *i*, while the second algorithm takes linear time whenever *k* is smaller than *n* by a log(*i*)*n* factor.
[src:line-segment-intersection/bentley-ottmann-algorithm] Both of these algorithms involve applying the Bentley–Ottmann algorithm to small random samples of the input.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] In geometry, an **intersection** between geometric objects (seen as sets of points) is a point, line, or curve common to two or more objects (such as lines, curves, planes, and surfaces).
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] The simplest case in Euclidean geometry is the line–line intersection between two distinct lines, which either is one point (sometimes called a *vertex*) or empty (if the lines are parallel).
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] Determination of the intersection of flats – linear geometric objects embedded in a higher-dimensional space – is a simple task of linear algebra, namely the solution of a system of linear equations.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] In general the determination of an intersection leads to non-linear equations, which can be solved numerically, for example using Newton iteration.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] Intersection problems between a line and a conic section (circle, ellipse, parabola, etc.) or a quadric (sphere, cylinder, hyperboloid, etc.) lead to quadratic equations that can be easily solved.
