[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] When the intersection of a sphere and a plane is not empty or a single point, it is a circle.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] Let *S* be a sphere with center *O*, *P* a plane which intersects *S*.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] Draw *OE* perpendicular to *P* and meeting *P* at *E*.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] Let *A* and *B* be any two different points in the intersection.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] Then *AOE* and *BOE* are right triangles with a common side, *OE*, and hypotenuses *AO* and *BO* equal.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] Therefore, the remaining sides *AE* and *BE* are equal.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] This proves that all points in the intersection are the same distance from the point *E* in the plane *P*, in other words all points in the intersection lie on a circle *C* with center *E*.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] This proves that the intersection of *P* and *S* is contained in *C*.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] Note that *OE* is the axis of the circle.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] Now consider a point *D* of the circle *C*.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] On the other hand, the triangles *AOE* and *DOE* are right triangles with a common side, *OE*, and legs *EA* and *ED* equal.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] Therefore, the hypotenuses *AO* and *DO* are equal, and equal to the radius of *S*, so that *D* lies in *S*.
[src:line-segment-intersection/intersection-geometry] This proves that *C* is contained in the intersection of *P* and *S*.
