[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] In Euclidean geometry, the **intersection of a line and a line** can be the empty set, a single point, or a line (if they coincide).
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] Distinguishing these cases and finding the intersection have uses, for example, in computer graphics, motion planning, and collision detection.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] In a Euclidean space, if two lines are not coplanar, they have no point of intersection and are called skew lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] Non-Euclidean geometry describes spaces in which one line may not be parallel to any other lines, such as a sphere, and spaces where multiple lines through a single point may all be parallel to another line.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] In spherical and elliptic geometries, every pair of lines intersects, while in hyperbolic geometry there exist infinitely many distinct lines through a given point that do not intersect a given line.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] Projective geometry provides a unifying framework in which these different behaviors can be described by extending the notion of intersection to include ideal points, so that any two distinct lines intersect in exactly one point.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] A necessary condition for two lines to intersect is that they are in the same plane—that is, are not skew lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] Satisfaction of this condition is equivalent to the tetrahedron with vertices at two of the points on one line and two of the points on the other line being degenerate in the sense of having zero volume.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] For the algebraic form of this condition, see Skew lines § Testing for skewness.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] First we consider the intersection of two lines *L*1 and *L*2 in two-dimensional space, with line *L*1 being defined by two distinct points (*x*1, *y*1) and (*x*2, *y*2), and line *L*2 being defined by two distinct points (*x*3, *y*3) and (*x*4, *y*4).
