[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] In spherical geometry, lines are represented by great circles, defined as the intersections of a sphere $S^{2}=\{x\in \mathbb {R} ^{3}:\|x\|=R\}$ with planes through the origin.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] Every pair of lines intersects in two antipodal points, so there are no parallel lines in spherical geometry.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] In elliptic geometry, the space may be regarded as a quotient of spherical geometry in which antipodal points are identified.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] Lines in this geometry correspond to great circles with antipodal points considered equivalent, so each pair of lines intersects in exactly one point.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] Unlike spherical geometry, this identification eliminates the distinction between the two intersection points, producing a finite but unbounded space without parallel lines.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] In hyperbolic geometry, line–line intersection behavior differs from that of Euclidean and positively curved geometries.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] Given a line $\ell$ and a point $P\not \in \ell$ , there exist infinitely many distinct lines through P that do not intersect $\ell$ .
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] Two lines may intersect in exactly one point, be asymptotically parallel, or be ultraparallel (disjoint with a common perpendicular).
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] This behavior reflects the constant negative Gaussian curvature $K<0$ of hyperbolic space and the failure of the Euclidean parallel postulate.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] Line–line intersection is therefore not guaranteed and depends on the incidence relations of the geometry rather than on metric distance alone.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] In projective geometry, any two distinct lines intersect in exactly one point by construction.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] This is achieved by adjoining ideal points (points at infinity), so that parallel lines in Euclidean geometry meet at a single projective point.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] Lines are modeled as one-dimensional projective subspaces, and incidence relations are fundamental, while notions of distance, angle, and curvature are not.
[src:line-segment-intersection/line-line-intersection] Projective geometry thus provides a unifying framework in which Euclidean, elliptic, and hyperbolic geometries can be studied via appropriate projective models.
[src:line-segment-intersection/sweep-line-algorithm] In computational geometry, a **sweep line algorithm** or **plane sweep algorithm** is an algorithmic paradigm that uses a conceptual *sweep line* or *sweep surface* to solve various problems in Euclidean space.
[src:line-segment-intersection/sweep-line-algorithm] It is one of the critical techniques in computational geometry.
[src:line-segment-intersection/sweep-line-algorithm] The idea behind algorithms of this type is to imagine that a line (often a vertical line) is swept or moved across the plane, stopping at some points.
[src:line-segment-intersection/sweep-line-algorithm] Geometric operations are restricted to geometric objects that either intersect or are in the immediate vicinity of the sweep line whenever it stops, and the complete solution is available once the line has passed over all objects.
[src:line-segment-intersection/sweep-line-algorithm] An application of the approach had led to a breakthrough in the computational complexity of geometric algorithms when Shamos and Hoey presented algorithms for line segment intersection in the plane in 1976.
[src:line-segment-intersection/sweep-line-algorithm] In particular, they described how a combination of the scanline approach with efficient data structures (self-balancing binary search trees) makes it possible to detect whether there are intersections among N segments in the plane in time complexity of O(*N* log *N*).
[src:line-segment-intersection/sweep-line-algorithm] The closely related Bentley–Ottmann algorithm uses a sweep line technique to report all K intersections among any N segments in the plane in time complexity of O((*N* + *K*) log *N*) and space complexity of O(*N*).
[src:line-segment-intersection/sweep-line-algorithm] Since then, this approach has been used to design efficient algorithms for a number of problems in computational geometry, such as the construction of the Voronoi diagram (Fortune's algorithm) and the Delaunay triangulation or boolean operations on polygons.
[src:line-segment-intersection/sweep-line-algorithm] Topological sweeping is a form of plane sweep with a simple ordering of processing points, which avoids the necessity of completely sorting the points; it allows some sweep line algorithms to be performed more efficiently.
[src:line-segment-intersection/sweep-line-algorithm] The sweeping approach may be generalised to higher dimensions.
